  "prompt": "How will terrorism stop if there is a ban on 500 and 1000 notes?",
  "response": "The demonetization of 500 and 1000 rupee notes in India in 2016 was primarily aimed at combating black money, counterfeiting, and corruption, not directly at stopping terrorism. While it may have had some indirect effects on terrorist financing, it did not completely stop terrorism. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Potential impacts on terrorism financing:\n- Disrupted cash flow for illegal activities\n- Made it harder to transport large amounts of cash\n- Reduced counterfeit currency circulation\n\n2. Limitations:\n- Terrorists could still use other methods to transfer funds\n- Alternative currencies and digital transactions remained possible\n- Some terrorist groups adapted to the new financial landscape\n\n3. Comprehensive approaches to countering terrorism typically involve:\n- Intelligence gathering\n- International cooperation\n- Addressing root causes\n- Cutting off financial support\n- Strengthening law enforcement\n- Diplomatic efforts\n\nDemonetization alone cannot completely stop terrorism. It was one of many measures to address financial irregularities and potential funding sources for illegal activities.\n\nEffective counter-terrorism requires a multi-pronged, collaborative approach involving various national and international strategies.",
